@Kelli 

Trade consists of imports plus exports. These will both affect the trade volume in South Korea. In general, Russia has been unable to import a lot of goods, so the decrease in trade with South Korea could primarily be a result in a decrease of Russian exports. Russia exports a lot of oil and gas. If South Korea decreases their purchase of these goods, what might be the implications of this for people who live in South Korea? 
Please return to this site when, by Friday, we will reveal the free link to the article that includes this graph plus several other graphs.  There, you can read about how Russian trade affects multiple countries.

@Ayoub 
It sounds like you are surprised that the majority of trade has increased? Were you expecting to see something different? You are not alone.   The International Monetary Fund predicts that the Russian economy will shrink this year by 3.4%.  

Please return to this site when, by Friday, we will reveal the free link to the article that includes this graph plus several other graphs.  There, you can read about the effect of reduced trade on Russia.

@Ms. Lasky's AP Language 2A 

You categorized and differentiated your “notices” nicely and have identified the multiple variables which are both categorical and quantitative. Distinguishing between trade volume and trade value is important. Do you have any predictions about what additional factors affect trade value? Doing a quick google search could answer your question, but I recommend making a prediction first! Also, what evidence from the graph could support your wonder with regard to proximity? Which countries are most proximal to Russia and are their changes in trade relatively the same? 
Please return to this site when, by Friday, we will reveal the free link to the article that includes this graph plus several other graphs.  There, you can read about the effect of reduced trade on Russia.

@Stella AOSE 
Identifying the largest percent change and wondering what’s going on in that situation is a nice strategy. I think your wonder about proximity between countries is thoughtful. Can you look for any evidence in the graphic to support your curiosity. Which countries are closest to Russia? Furthest? And how have their percentages changed? And, if it is not proximity, what do the countries that have increased trade with Russia have in common? 

Don’t forget to come back on Friday. Then, you will find out what may have caused these changes in trade.
